One of the people is taking a trip to Cancun.  Her husband, daughter, son, and a friend of their daughter are going.  The husband did not call the parents of the daughters friend before purchasing the ticket.  Now they find out that the children lied and the friend of the daughter cannot go.  Post 9-11-01 you cannot transfer tickets to another flight passenger.  <br>
<br>
The kicker.<br>
The office employees are irate that this inconvenience to their lives all because a bunch of "towel heads".  (no offence intended just putting forth their point of view).<br>
<br>
Now I asked them if they have ever been to another country for an extended amount of time to see what security is like in other countries.  Unanimously the answer was "No".<br>
<br>
I then asked them what they were willing to sacrifice in order to increase security and save lives at the detriment to their accepted lifestyle.  Again I was dumbfounded "Nothing, we should be able to increase security and not have to change anything."<br>
<br>
I served in the USMC, I've traveled to south America (lived there for 3 months Colombia), Asia (Japan lived in Osaka 3 months non military), Canada (though they have accents I don’t view Canada as much different from the US though my time there admittedly was short), and of course trips to Mexico.  I realize that the US is just plane LAZY when it comes to what the average citizen is willing to sacrifice for their country in matters of security, economics, and time invested taking the place of other pursuits."<br>
<br>
I ask you this from people in countries other than the US.<br>
<br>
What would you give up that is accepted as a "God given right" in your country to ensure that you have food on the table at night, your children will grow up to have food on their tables, and you are allowed to grow old and die of natural causes?<br>
<br>
I know what I'm willing to sacrifice for those 3 simple things it just surprises me that I meet people who value a plane ticket over national security.  Seems to me priorities are out of whack here.<br>
